additional_information: Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is an infection of the female reproductive organs. It most often occurs when sexually transmitted bacteria spread from your vagina to your uterus, fallopian tubes or ovaries.
diagnosis: Moderate risk of Pelvic Inflamatory Disease (PID)
general_advice: Practice safe or protected sex.|Get yourself tested and get your partner also tested.|Avoid having sex until the symptoms subside at least.|Do not douche
causes: Many types of bacteria can cause PID. These bacteria are usually acquired during unprotected sex. Less commonly these bacteria can enter your reproductive tract during menstruation, after childbirth, miscarriage or abortion.

additional_information: In many cases, a woman can experience painful sex if there is not sufficient vaginal lubrication. When this occurs, the pain can be resolved if the female becomes more relaxed, if the amount of foreplay is increased, or if the couple uses a sexual lubricant. In other cases a woman can experience painful sex due to other psychological or physical issues.
general_advice: Increasing the time of your foreplay may be helpful in arousal and natural lubrication.|You may also try using water-based lubrication.|Talking to your partner always helps.|If the problem persists please consult a gynaecologist to clear your doubts.

additional_information: Common Sexually transmitted infections, such as chlamydia, gonorrhea genital herpes or Vaginitis can cause vaginal irritation, which can cause pain during sex. They are easily treatable and avoidable too.
general_advice: Practice safe or protected sex. Get yourself tested and get your partner also tested. Avoid having sex until the symptoms subside at least. Do not douche

additional_information: Endometriosis happens when tissue that is similar to the tissue that lines the woman's uterus, grows outside of the uterus. Sex or Penetration can pull or stretch the irritated tissue and can thus cause pain. About 25 million women in India have endometriosis.
general_advice: Exercise regularly|You can use heat packs for pain if it exists|Take a healthy diet|Some positions involving shallow penetration like spooning which put less pressure on areas of the pelvis that contain endometrial tissue can help reduce pain during sexual activity

additional_information: Experiencing painful sex after giving birth is common. About 50+% of women have reported painful sex (dyspareunia) after giving birth. Usually, it's reported to occur at about 6 weeks after childbirth and can continue up to 6 months postpartum or longer.
diagnosis: Moderate risk of post partum blues. Counselling recommended
general_advice: Exercise when you can.|Maintain a healthy diet|Create time for yourself|Make time to rest

In other cases a woman can experience painful sex due to other psychological or physical issues.
diagnosis: This is normal case of low libido
general_advice: With estrogen levels falling as women approach and pass menopause. The resulting dryness and thinning of vaginal tissues can make penetration and intercourse to be uncomfortable for many women. The discomfort can range from a feeling of dryness to a feeling of vaginal/tightness/to severe pain during sex. After sex, some women feel soreness in their vagina or burning in their vulva or vagina. Over time, and without treatment, the inflammation that may result from infrequent sex without sufficient vaginal lubrication can lead to tearing and bleeding of vaginal tissues during sex. All these things together can lead to anxiety around sex and lead to decreased libido and worsening of pain (aka dyspareunia)
